Problem statement¶

An online news portal aims to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. Every visitor to the website takes certain actions based on their interest. The company plans to analyze these interests and wants to determine whether a new feature will be effective or not. Companies often analyze users' responses to two variants of a product to decide which of the two variants is more effective.Using a/b testing technique we will determine whether a new feature attracts users based on a chosen metric.

Objective¶

Perform the statistical analysis to answer the following questions:

  1. Explore the dataset and extract insights using Exploratory Data Analysis.
  2. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page?
  3. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?
  4. Does the converted status depend on the preferred language? [Hint: Create a contingency table using the pandas.crosstab() function]
  5. Is the mean time spent on the new page same for the different language users?
  • Consider a significance level of 0.05 for all tests.

Data dictionary¶

  1. user_id - This represents the user ID of the person visiting the website.
  2. group - This represents whether the user belongs to the first group (control) or the second group (treatment).
  3. landing_page - This represents whether the landing page is new or old.
  4. time_spent_on_the_page - This represents the time (in minutes) spent by the user on the landing page.
  5. converted - This represents whether the user gets converted to a subscriber of the news portal or not.
  6. language_preferred - This represents the language chosen by the user to view the landing page.

1. Explore the dataset and extract insights using Exploratory Data Analysis.¶

2. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page?¶

Step 1: Let's write the null and alternative hypothesis¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0: \mu_1>=\mu_2$ Users spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a: \mu_1<\mu_2 $ Users do not spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page

Step 2: Select appropriate test¶

Using one-way anova test using the f_oneway function

Step 3: Calculate p-value¶

In [68]:
# separate the time_spent_on_page with respect to the landing page
time_spent_on_new_page = df[df['landing_page']=='new']['time_spent_on_the_page']
time_spent_on_old_page = df[df['landing_page']=='old']['time_spent_on_the_page']
In [69]:
# perform one-way anova test using the f_oneway function from scipy.stats library
test_stat, p_value = stats.f_oneway(time_spent_on_new_page, time_spent_on_old_page)
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.000263224705619001

Step 4: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

The significance level is 0.05¶
In [70]:
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.000263224705619001 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 5: Inference based on the p-value¶

Since the p-value is less than the 5% significance level, we reject the null hypothesis. Hence, we have enough statistical evidence to say that Users do not spend more time on the new landing page than the old landing page

3. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

In [71]:
sns.jointplot(df['converted'], df['landing_page'],hue=df['group'], kind="hist"); #visual analysis

Observation¶

  • Converted users for new landing page are more than the old landing page.

Step 1: Determining null and alternative hypothesis¶

The null hypothesis is

$H_0: >= $ The conversion rate for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page

against the alternate hypothesis

$H_a: < $ The conversion rate for the new page is not greater than the conversion rate for the old page

Step 2: Checking convertion rate for new and old page¶

The total numbers of users in control and treatment group are 50 and 50 respectively
In [76]:
print(f' The proportions of users in control and treatment group are {round(21/50,2)}, {round(33/50,2)} respectively')

 The proportions of users in control and treatment group are 0.42, 0.66 respectively

Step 3: Selecting appropriate test¶

The formulated hypotheses are concerned with proportions. A test of proportions can be used to analyse the hypotheses and draw a conclusion. We shall use a Proportions Z test for this problem.

Step 4: Calculate the p-value¶

In [77]:
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest
# find the p-value using proportion_ztest
stat, pval = proportions_ztest([control_group, treatment_group] , [n_control, n_treatment], alternative = 'larger')

# print the p-value
print('The p-value is '+ str(pval))

The p-value is 0.9919736917959437

Step 5: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [78]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if pval < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {pval} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {pval} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.9919736917959437 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Step 6: Inference based on the p-value¶

At the 5% significance level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence we do not have enough statistical evidence to say that the conversion rate for the new page is greater than the conversion rate for the old page

Step 1: Define null and alternative hypotheses¶

$H_0:$ The converted users (status-yes/no(1/0)) depend on the preferred language

$H_a:$ The converted users (status-yes/no(1/0)) does not depend on the preferred language

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

The formulated hypotheses can be tested using a Chi-square test of independence of attributes, concerning the two categorical variables, (The converted users depend on the preferred language or not)

Step 3: Significance level¶

Here, we select α= 0.05.

Step 4: Data preparation¶

In [83]:
data= contingency_table
data
Out[83]:

converted

yes 21 15 18

Step 5: Calculate p - value¶

In [84]:
# use chi2_contingency() to find the p-value
from   scipy.stats import chi2_contingency
chi2, pval, dof, exp_freq = chi2_contingency(data)
# print the p-value
print('The p-value is', pval)

The p-value is 0.21298887487543447

Step 6: Compare p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [85]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if pval < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {pval} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {pval} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.21298887487543447 is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Inference based on the p-value¶

At the 5% significance level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Hence we do not have enough statistical evidence to say that the converted status depend on the preferred language.

Step 1: Define null and alternate hypotheses¶

$H_0$ : The mean time spent on the new page is same for the different language users.

$H_a$ : The mean time spent on the new page is different for the different language users

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This is a problem, concerning three population means. One-way ANOVA could be the appropriate test here provided normality and equality of variance assumptions are verified.

For testing of normality, Shapiro-Wilk’s test is applied to the response variable.

For equality of variance, Levene test is applied to the response variable.

Shapiro-Wilk’s test¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0:$ The time spent on the page follows a normal distribution

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a:$ The time spent on the page do not not follow a normal distribution

In [91]:
# Assumption 1: Normality
# Use the shapiro function for the scipy.stats library for this test

# find the p-value
w, p_value = stats.shapiro(df['time_spent_on_the_page']) 
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.5643684267997742

Since p-value of the test is large than the 5% significance level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis that the response follows the normal distribution.

Levene’s test¶

We will test the null hypothesis

$H_0$: All the population variances are equal

against the alternative hypothesis

$H_a$: At least one variance is different from the rest

In [92]:
#Assumption 2: Homogeneity of Variance
# use levene function from scipy.stats library for this test

# find the p-value
statistic, p_value = stats.levene(df[df['language_preferred']=='Spanish']['time_spent_on_the_page'],
                            df[df['language_preferred']=='French']['time_spent_on_the_page'],
                            df[df['language_preferred']=='English']['time_spent_on_the_page'])
print('The p-value is', p_value)

The p-value is 0.06515086840327314

Since the p-value is larger than the 5% significance level, we fail to reject the null hypothesis of homogeneity of variances.

Prepare the data¶

In [93]:
a = df[df['language_preferred']=='Spanish']['time_spent_on_the_page']
b = df[df['language_preferred']=='French']['time_spent_on_the_page']
c = df[df['language_preferred']=='English']['time_spent_on_the_page']

Calculate the p-value¶

In [94]:
# perform one-way anova test using the f_oneway function from scipy.stats library
test_stat, p_value = stats.f_oneway(a, b, c)
print('The p-value is ', p_value)

The p-value is  0.8665610536012648
